text.text:
It is with a heavy heart that I share that Michael (Mike) R. Quinlan, former CEO and Chairman of McDonalds, has passed away.

Mikes storied career with McDonald's began in 1963 as a summer mail clerk. In fact, he got his start at McDonalds through a serendipitous connection, as he was the college roommate of one of June Martinos sons. June, a legendary figure in McDonalds history, was Ray Krocs first bookkeeper and played a pivotal role in shaping the franchise model.

In his more than 35 years with McDonalds, he rose through the System, spending time in the restaurants and our headquarters to ultimately lead the business as President and COO in 1982, CEO in 1987, and Chairman of the Board in 1990.

Mike, affectionately known as Q, has a legacy that extends far beyond the boardroom. He was a passionate philanthropist and lifelong supporter of education. His generous contributions to Loyola University Chicago, where he studied and later served as Chairman of the Board, led to the creation of the Quinlan School of Business, Loyola University Chicago. He also championed community initiatives, including the construction of a Ronald McDonald House near Loyolas Medical Center. Mikes impact on our brand, our people, and our values will be felt for generations.

We extend our deepest condolences to Mikes family, friends, and all who had the privilege of working with him. Let us honor his memory by continuing to lead with the same care, commitment, and courage that defined his remarkable journey.

text.text:
As long as McDonald's has been around, weve stayed true to a simple promise: delicious food at great value. That promise matters now more than ever  and were not taking our foot off the gas.

Thanks to CNBCs Squawk Box for inviting me to share more about the return of our Extra Value Meals in the U.S., our global commitment to core menu items, and the bigger picture behind it all. What energizes me most is seeing how our Franchisees, suppliers, and employees are rallying together with purpose  making sure McDonalds continues to deliver those everyday feel-good moments, at a price that feels just right.

text.text:
Im excited to share that Emily Reasor will join McDonald's this month as Senior Vice President and Chief Strategy Officer. This hire signals our intent to make strategy a dynamic capability  one that drives execution, unlocks growth, and strengthens our competitive edge.
  
As we unlock the next chapter of our growth, Emily will work across our global business to identify new opportunities, embed strategic discipline into how we operate, and ensure our priorities remain anchored in what matters most to our customers, communities and the McDonalds system.
  
Welcome to the McFamily, Emily - I look forward to all of the exciting work to come.

text.text:
When you put people first, everything else follows. This is the belief that guided Ray Kroc when he opened the first franchised McDonald's restaurant in Des Plaines, Illinois, 70 years ago. Its the belief that remains deeply embedded in our business, from our restaurant crew members to our franchisees to our suppliers to our corporate teams. 

Reflecting on my ten years under the Golden Arches, my favorite memories are rooted in our restaurants and the incredible people who make McDonalds a great place to work. In celebration of our 70th anniversary and Founders Day, I want to shine a light on the folks who keep Rays spirit alive in our restaurants and beyond. Each day, you make McDonalds proud.  

While weve evolved over the years, our shared commitment to our values and serving our customers and communities hasn't changed. I'm confident we will continue to make delicious feel-good moments for generations to come. #WeMakeMcDonalds
